16:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-12","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Rate Mechanics"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Both KuCoin and Phemex use standard 8-hour funding intervals with rates calculated from premium and interest components. KuCoin's rates tend to be more volatile due to higher retail participation, while Phemex maintains tighter spreads around the index price due to its derivatives focus. KuCoin offers more altcoin perpetuals where funding rates can reach extreme levels, whereas Phemex concentrates on major pairs with more stable rate patterns."}]]}]
17:["$","$L19",null,{"items":[{"question":"Which exchange offers better maker fees for funding arbitrage?","answer":"Phemex provides 0.01% maker fees compared to KuCoin's 0.02%, offering 50% savings for market makers. This fee difference significantly impacts arbitrage profitability over multiple funding cycles."},{"question":"How do funding rate volatilities compare between these platforms?","answer":"KuCoin typically shows higher funding rate volatility, especially on altcoin perpetuals, due to retail-heavy participation. Phemex maintains more stable rates focused on major cryptocurrencies with professional trader base."},{"question":"Which platform has better liquidity for large arbitrage positions?","answer":"KuCoin generally offers deeper liquidity across more trading pairs, particularly altcoins. Phemex has concentrated liquidity in major pairs but may show gaps during high volatility periods."},{"question":"Do both exchanges support API trading for automated strategies?","answer":"Both provide robust REST and WebSocket APIs for automated trading. Phemex offers cleaner derivatives-focused endpoints, while KuCoin includes additional spot and margin trading integration options."}]}]
